A person convicted of an eligible felony, or eligible felonies from the same occurrence or related course of events, may petition the convicting court. ("https://law.justia.com/codes/wyoming/title-7/chapter-13/article-15/section-7-13-1502/")
Eligibility checklist

Requirement Rule
Waiting period At least 10 years since sentence expiration, including probation
Court programs Any court-ordered program must be completed
Restitution Court-ordered restitution must be paid in full
Other felonies Other than the felony/felonies being expunged, petitioner must not have previously pled guilty, pled no contest, or been convicted of a felony
Firearm bar Felony must not have involved use or attempted use of a firearm, except certain Title 23 offenses
Danger finding Court must find petitioner is not a substantial danger to self, victim, or society
One-time limit Only one felony conviction expungement under this section
Filing fee $300
Service Verified petition served on prosecutor and DCI
Objection window Prosecutor/victim has 90 days to object
Effect on rights Expungement under 7-13-1502 restores rights removed because of the conviction
The statute sets the 10-year wait, restitution/program completion rules, other-felony bar, firearm bar, $300 fee, 90-day objection window, court sealing/DCI transmission, one-time limit, and restoration-of-rights language. (

"https://law.justia.com/codes/wyoming/title-7/chapter-13/article-15/section-7-13-1502/")
Felony exclusions
Wilma should flag likely ineligible/manual review if the felony is:
a violent felony under W.S. 6-1-104(a)(xii);
aggravated homicide by vehicle;
drug-induced homicide;
sexual assault or related sexual offense under W.S. 6-2-301 through 6-2-320;
certain domestic battery offenses;
child abuse;
aggravated assault/battery on a corrections or detention officer;
sexual exploitation of children;
incest;
endangering children with controlled substances;
bribery;
disarming a peace officer;
escape from official detention / violent or armed escape;
weapons offenses under W.S. 6-8-101 or 6-8-102;
any offense subject to sex-offender registration under W.S. 7-19-302(g) through (j). ("https://law.justia.com/codes/wyoming/title-7/chapter-13/article-15/section-7-13-1502/")
Wilma trap: Felony deferred prosecution is a danger zone. In Lynch v. State, the Wyoming Supreme Court held that 7-13-1502 applies to people convicted of felonies; a completed deferred prosecution where the guilty plea was withdrawn and the case dismissed did not create a felony conviction to expunge. ("https://law.justia.com/cases/wyoming/supreme-court/2026/s-25-0140.html")

Wilma should start with:

1 Wyoming DCI criminal history;
2 court docket from the convicting/dismissing court;
3 certified disposition;
4 sentencing order;
5 probation/sentence completion proof;
6 restitution payment proof;
7 DCI or FBI record if the user needs broad background-check review.
Wyoming DCI explains that Wyoming criminal-history records are created when an arrest fingerprint card is submitted; if no arrest fingerprint card is submitted, the arrest will not be available on the state or FBI criminal-history record, and DCI cannot create an arrest event from court documents alone. ("https://wyomingdci.wyo.gov/criminal-justice-information-services-cjis/criminal-records-unit?utm_source=chatgpt.com")
Wilma should collect:
full legal name and prior names;
date of birth;
county and court;
case number;
arrest date;
charge date;
original charge and final charge;
final disposition;
whether all charges from the incident ended without conviction;
whether there was a deferred prosecution/disposition under 7-13-301, 35-7-1037, or former 7-13-203;
whether the case was misdemeanor, felony, municipal, juvenile, diversion, or deferral;
sentencing date;
probation completion date;
program completion date;
restitution payment date;
whether firearm use or attempted use was involved;
whether any sex-offender registration was required;
whether any other felony plea/no-contest/conviction exists;
whether there are pending charges;
whether there are identifiable victims;
whether trafficking/coercion facts are present.

Step 1 - Adult or juvenile/minor?
Ask:

Was this an adult case, or were you under 18 when it happened?

If juvenile/minor, check 14-6-241 first.
Step 2 - Conviction or no conviction?
Ask:

Did the case end in conviction/guilty/no contest, or was it dismissed, acquitted, declined, or never charged?

No conviction 7-13-1401 check.Misdemeanor conviction/plea 7-13-1501 check.Felony conviction 7-13-1502 check.
Step 3 - Deferred disposition trap
Ask:

Was this handled through deferred prosecution, first-offender treatment, probation before judgment, or a dismissal after completing probation?

If yes, flag manual review. Wyoming treats deferred dispositions differently depending on whether the route is non-conviction, misdemeanor, felony, juvenile, or drug-specific.
Step 4 - Firearm / sex / violence / victim checks
Ask:

Did the offense involve a gun, sex-offender registration, violence, a child victim, domestic battery, weapons, escape, bribery, or harm to a patient by a health-care provider?

These are major eligibility danger zones.
Step 5 - Completion dates
Ask:

When did you finish probation, court-ordered programs, and restitution?

For misdemeanors and felonies, the clock runs from completion/expiration of sentence terms, not merely conviction date.
